500|$|During {{their trip}} to Peru in June 1995, {{sponsored}} by The Pembroke Hill School, Farrar met and befriended Margaret Hacker, whose children also attended the school. Hacker was {{a registered nurse}} married to an anesthesiologist, and also unhappy with her marriage. The two began an [...] affair shortly after both families returned from Peru. In late July, Farrar again asked Green for a divorce. Green responded hysterically and told the children that their father was leaving them. Green was especially upset that a <b>broken</b> <b>home</b> might later disqualify the children from debutante {{events such as the}} Belles of the American Royal.|$|E
500|$|The album's {{lyrics are}} {{described}} as 'politically, socially and personally conscious', incorporating themes such as corporate greed, racism and {{growing up in a}} <b>broken</b> <b>home.</b> Butler says it is [...] "an ode to the disenfranchised and disaffected youth" [...] and about accepting that we will never be perfect. Some of the lyrics reflect on his early life where he had to raise his sister and grow up at the same time. He added ambiguity to the lyrics to [...] "facilitate" [...] ideas for the listeners. Freeman said that the lyrics [...] "reveal just how self-aware he is, which is a good counterpoint to those who feel that his constant vocalizing equates to selfishness." ...|$|E
500|$|In Frank's backstory, he is {{a product}} of a <b>broken</b> <b>home,</b> born to a {{criminal}} father and an alcoholic mother. His father was sent to prison and his mother became incapable of looking after him. As a result, Frank became wayward, but that changed after he was fostered by Pippa and Tom. Frank's ethnicity is Greek Australian; and he fills the role of the serial's first heart-throb. He is characterised as having [...] "streetwise ways" [...] and a [...] "disarming smile". Frank has rock and roll ambitions because he has never been academically successful. He faced hardship to get through school. Frank only just managed to pass his exams into Year 10. However, his ambitions are reachable as the [...] "only thing" [...] he is good at is playing the guitar. Frank wants to get a job and form his own band.|$|E
