40|$|Includes bibliographical {{references}} (pages 75 - 77) A {{sample of}} 308 {{high school students}} were utilized to measure role attitudes towards marriage for their future husband or wife and to observe if there were differences in the attitudes of adolescents from intact homes versus adolescents from <b>broken</b> <b>homes.</b> A questionnaire was compiled from related literature and the measurement instruments, which were given to these students. The sample was drawn from high school students at El Camino High School and Simi Valley High School. The hypotheses were derived from the theory of family sociologist Bernard Farber (1964) who suggested {{that the nature of}} parent-child interaction in the American family was changing in relation to their attitudes towards various aspects of the familial institution. Further, he theorized that the nature of such interaction between parents and children is crucial in the stability or change within the family. The hypotheses of this study were: I. Are there significant differences in the effects of sex, and intact versus <b>broken</b> <b>homes</b> upon adolescent attitudes towards the institution of marriage and the family. Specifically, the attitudes of: a. wanting to marry b. age anticipate marrying c. length adolescent knows prospective mate d. wanting children e. how many children II. Are there significant differences in the effects of sex, and intact versus <b>broken</b> <b>homes</b> upon adolescent views of the qualities they desire in a prospective mate. Specifically, views towards: a. congruence of religion b. congruence of race c. educational expectations d. financial expectations III. What effects do sex differences, and intact versus <b>broken</b> <b>homes</b> have upon how adolescents view their own prospective families with respect to traditional versus egalitarian marital roles. (See more in text...|$|R
